{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532682"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:29:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:29:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14700"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14700"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.01,0.91,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7393"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58081"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7393"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14700"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43540"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2942"},{"type":"tags","id":"3513"},{"type":"tags","id":"4534"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18032"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58081"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her second urinary tract infection in six months. She also reports having had two skin infections requiring antibiotics in the past year. She has type 2 diabetes mellitus diagnosed eight years ago, obesity with BMI 34 kg/m2, and hypertension. Her medications include metformin, gliclazide, perindopril, and amlodipine. She works as a receptionist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits except for blood pressure 152/89 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecent investigations show:\u003Cbr /\u003E\u2022 Random glucose 13.2 mmol/L (3.9-7.8)\u003Cbr /\u003E\u2022 Sodium 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003Cbr /\u003E\u2022 Potassium 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003Cbr /\u003E\u2022 Urea 6.0 mmol/L (3.0-8.0)\u003Cbr /\u003E\u2022 Creatinine 110 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003Cbr /\u003E\u2022 HbA1c 8.2%\u003Cbr /\u003E\u2022 Urine dipstick: protein ++\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate long-term strategy to reduce the frequency of infections?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Weight loss program","Immunological investigation","Improved glycaemic control","Long-term prophylactic antibiotics","Optimise anti-proteinuric therapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with recurrent infections in the context of poorly controlled type 2 diabetes mellitus, as evidenced by elevated random glucose (13.2 mmol/L) and HbA1c (8.2%). Poor glycaemic control is a well-established risk factor for increased susceptibility to infections, particularly urinary tract and skin infections. \u003Cstrong\u003EImproved glycaemic control\u003C/strong\u003E is therefore the most appropriate strategy to reduce infection frequency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a \u003Cstrong\u003Eweight loss program\u003C/strong\u003E would be beneficial for this patient\u0027s overall health and may indirectly improve glycaemic control, it is not the most direct approach to addressing the immediate problem of recurrent infections. The patient\u0027s BMI of 34 kg/m2 indicates obesity, but this is not as strongly linked to infection risk as poor glycaemic control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmunological investigation\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate if the patient had normal glycaemic control and was still experiencing frequent infections. Given the clear evidence of poor diabetes control, this would be premature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong-term prophylactic antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E might prevent some infections but would not address the underlying cause and could lead to antimicrobial resistance and infections such as \u003Cem\u003EClostridium difficile\u003C/em\u003E. This approach can be considered for cases where the primary cause cannot be modified or has been optimally managed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptimise anti-proteinuric therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would be important for managing diabetic nephropathy (as evidenced by proteinuria), but this would not directly address the increased infection risk. The priority should be improving glycaemic control, which would also help prevent further progression of diabetic complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Optimal glycaemic control is crucial for preventing recurrent infections in patients with diabetes."],"references":["Zhou K, Lansang MC. Diabetes Mellitus and Infections. In: StatPearls [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK569326/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43540"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14700"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43540"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-28T20:58:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T20:58:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7393"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58081"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null